PMCW Radar: Phase-Modulated Continuous Wave¶

Introduction¶

This notebook demonstrates PMCW (Phase-Modulated Continuous Wave) radar—an emerging radar technology for automotive applications that offers significant advantages over FMCW, including larger maximum velocity measurements, better interference mitigation, and MIMO compatibility. PMCW is becoming increasingly important for autonomous vehicle sensing.

What is PMCW Radar?¶

Phase Modulation Concept:

Unlike FMCW which modulates frequency, PMCW modulates the phase of a continuous carrier signal according to a specific code sequence. The transmitted signal can be expressed as:

$$s(t) = A \cos(2\pi f_c t + \phi(t))$$

Where:

  • $A$ = Amplitude
  • $f_c$ = Carrier frequency (constant, e.g., 24.125 GHz)
  • $\phi(t)$ = Time-varying phase (modulated by code)

Binary Phase Shift Keying (BPSK):

Most PMCW radars use BPSK where phase switches between 0° and 180°:

  • Code bit = +1 → Phase = 0°
  • Code bit = -1 → Phase = 180°

PMCW vs. FMCW Comparison¶

FMCW Characteristics:

  • Frequency modulation (chirp)
  • Range from beat frequency
  • Velocity from Doppler across chirps
  • Limited maximum velocity (Doppler ambiguity)
  • Sensitive to mutual interference

PMCW Characteristics:

  • Phase modulation (code sequence)
  • Range from code correlation
  • Velocity from Doppler across pulses
  • Much larger maximum velocity
  • Better interference rejection
  • MIMO-friendly (orthogonal codes)

PMCW Advantages¶

1. Large Maximum Velocity:

PMCW can measure velocities far beyond FMCW limits:

$$v_{max,PMCW} = \frac{c}{2f_c T_{code}}$$

Where $T_{code}$ is the duration of one code chip (e.g., 4 ns).

For 24 GHz with 4 ns chips: $$v_{max} = \frac{3 \times 10^8}{2 \times 24.125 \times 10^9 \times 4 \times 10^{-9}} \approx 1550 \text{ m/s}$$

Compare to FMCW: typically 30-100 m/s

2. Interference Mitigation:

  • Uncorrelated interferers: Other radars' codes appear as noise
  • Low cross-correlation: Codes designed for minimal interference
  • Spreading gain: Processing gain from code length
  • Robustness: Less affected by mutual radar interference

3. MIMO Compatibility:

  • Orthogonal codes: Each TX channel uses different code
  • Code separation: Distinguish multiple simultaneous transmitters
  • Virtual array: Create large aperture from few antennas
  • Angular resolution: Improved angle estimation

4. Flexible Waveform:

  • Code design freedom: Choose codes for specific properties
  • Adaptability: Change codes dynamically
  • Coexistence: Multiple radars with orthogonal codes

PMCW Principles¶

Range Measurement:

Range is determined by matched filtering (correlation) with the transmitted code:

$$R = \frac{c \cdot \tau}{2}$$

Where $\tau$ is the time delay corresponding to the correlation peak position.

Range Resolution:

$$\Delta R = \frac{c \cdot T_{chip}}{2}$$

For $T_{chip} = 4$ ns: $\Delta R = 0.6$ m

Velocity Measurement:

Velocity is extracted from Doppler shift across multiple code sequences (pulses):

$$v = \frac{f_d \cdot c}{2f_c}$$

Where $f_d$ is measured via FFT across pulses.

Phase Code Sequences¶

Desired Properties:

  1. Low autocorrelation sidelobes: Sharp peak, low background
  2. Low cross-correlation: Different codes don't interfere
  3. Good Doppler tolerance: Performance maintained with motion
  4. Long code length: Better processing gain and resolution

Common Code Families:

  • Barker codes: Excellent autocorrelation (length ≤ 13)
  • M-sequences (Maximum-length): Good properties, long codes
  • Gold codes: Low cross-correlation pairs
  • Kasami codes: Large sets with good correlation
  • Golay codes: Perfect autocorrelation in pairs
  • Zadoff-Chu sequences: Constant amplitude, low correlation

PMCW Signal Processing¶

1. Matched Filtering:

Correlate received signal with transmitted code:

$$R[n] = \sum_{k=0}^{N-1} s[k] \cdot c[k-n]$$

Where:

  • $s[k]$ = Received signal
  • $c[k]$ = Code sequence
  • $n$ = Delay index → Range

2. Doppler Processing:

Apply FFT across pulses for each range bin:

$$S[m, n] = \sum_{p=0}^{P-1} R[p, n] \cdot w[p] \cdot e^{-j2\pi mp/P}$$

Where:

  • $p$ = Pulse index
  • $n$ = Range bin
  • $w[p]$ = Window function
  • $m$ = Doppler bin → Velocity

MIMO Implementation¶

Spatial Multiplexing:

Multiple TX antennas transmit different orthogonal codes simultaneously:

  1. TX1 transmits code1
  2. TX2 transmits code2 (orthogonal to code1)
  3. RX receives superposition
  4. Matched filtering separates TX1 and TX2 contributions
  5. Virtual array formed from TX-RX combinations

Angular Resolution:

With $N_{TX}$ transmitters and $N_{RX}$ receivers:

  • Physical elements: $N_{TX} + N_{RX}$
  • Virtual elements: $N_{TX} \times N_{RX}$

Example: 2 TX + 4 RX = 8 virtual elements (4× improvement)

Automotive PMCW Applications¶

Use Cases:

  • Long-range detection: Highway driving (200+ m)
  • High-speed targets: Oncoming traffic (closing > 200 km/h)
  • Dense scenarios: Multiple vehicles, pedestrians
  • Interference environments: Parking garages, tunnels
  • MIMO radar: 4D imaging (range, velocity, azimuth, elevation)

Advantages for Automotive:

  • Handles high relative velocities
  • Robust to other radars
  • Scalable to large MIMO arrays
  • Good coexistence in dense radar environments

Modulation Hierarchy in RadarSimPy¶

RadarSimPy supports a comprehensive modulation hierarchy:

|                       prp
|                  +-----------+
|
|            +---f[1]--->  /            /            /
|                         /            /            /
|                        /            /            /
|                       /            /            /
|                      /            /            /     ...
|                     /            /            /
|                    /            /            /
|                   /            /            /
|      +---f[0]--->/            /            /
|
|                  +-------+
|                 t[0]    t[1]
|
|    Pulse         +--------------------------------------+
|    modulation    |pulse_amp[0]|pulse_amp[1]|pulse_amp[2]|  ...
|                  |pulse_phs[0]|pulse_phs[1]|pulse_phs[2]|  ...
|                  +--------------------------------------+
|
|    Waveform      +--------------------------------------+
|    modulation    |           amp / phs / mod_t          |  ...
|                  +--------------------------------------+

Three Modulation Levels:

  1. Frequency/Time (f, t): Chirp definition (FMCW)
  2. Pulse Modulation: Pulse-to-pulse amplitude/phase
  3. Waveform Modulation (mod_t, phs): Intra-pulse phase coding (PMCW)

### Convert Binary Codes to Phase (degrees) ###

# Initialize phase arrays
phase_code1 = np.zeros(np.shape(code1))
phase_code2 = np.zeros(np.shape(code2))

# Binary Phase Shift Keying (BPSK) mapping:
# +1 → 0° phase
# -1 → 180° phase
phase_code1[np.where(code1 == 1)] = 0     # Positive chip: 0 degrees
phase_code1[np.where(code1 == -1)] = 180  # Negative chip: 180 degrees
phase_code2[np.where(code2 == 1)] = 0     # Positive chip: 0 degrees
phase_code2[np.where(code2 == -1)] = 180  # Negative chip: 180 degrees

### Define Modulation Timing ###

# Chip duration: 4 ns per chip
# Total code duration: 255 chips × 4 ns = 1020 ns = 1.02 μs
t_mod1 = np.arange(0, len(phase_code1)) * 4e-9  # Time array for code1 (seconds)
t_mod2 = np.arange(0, len(phase_code2)) * 4e-9  # Time array for code2 (seconds)

Radar System Configuration¶

Configure PMCW radar with 2-channel MIMO using orthogonal phase codes.

Transmitter Configuration¶

Set up two transmitter channels with different phase code sequences for MIMO operation.

Transmitter Parameters:

  • Carrier Frequency: 24.125 GHz (constant, no frequency modulation)
  • Pulse Duration: 2.1 μs (includes 1.02 μs code + guard time)
  • Transmit Power: 20 dBm (~100 mW)
  • Number of Pulses: 256 (for Doppler processing)
  • Modulation: Phase codes via mod_t and phs arrays

MIMO Channel Configuration:

  • TX Channel 1:

    • Location: (0, 0, 0) m
    • Phase code: code1 (255 chips @ 4 ns)
    • Enables spatial diversity

  • TX Channel 2:

    • Location: (1, 0, 0) m → 1m offset in X-axis
    • Phase code: code2 (orthogonal to code1)
    • Creates virtual aperture with RX

Simultaneous Transmission:

Both TX channels transmit simultaneously at the same carrier frequency but with different phase codes. The orthogonal codes enable separation at the receiver via matched filtering.

In [ ]:
# Import radar modules
from radarsimpy import Radar, Transmitter, Receiver

### Define TX Channel 1 with Phase Code 1 ###
tx_channel_1 = dict(
    location=(0, 0, 0),     # TX1 antenna position at origin
    mod_t=t_mod1,           # Phase modulation timing (255 points × 4 ns)
    phs=phase_code1,        # Phase sequence for channel 1 (0° or 180°)
)

### Define TX Channel 2 with Phase Code 2 ###
tx_channel_2 = dict(
    location=(1, 0, 0),     # TX2 antenna position 1m offset in X
    mod_t=t_mod2,           # Phase modulation timing (same as TX1)
    phs=phase_code2,        # Phase sequence for channel 2 (orthogonal code)
)

### Create PMCW Transmitter ###
tx = Transmitter(
    f=24.125e9,             # Carrier frequency: 24.125 GHz (constant, no chirp)
    t=2.1e-6,               # Pulse duration: 2.1 μs (includes code + guard time)
    tx_power=20,            # Transmit power: 20 dBm (~100 mW)
    pulses=256,             # Number of pulses: 256 (for Doppler processing)
    channels=[tx_channel_1, tx_channel_2],  # 2-channel MIMO configuration
)

Receiver Configuration¶

Configure receiver for high-speed sampling to capture phase-modulated signal.

Receiver Parameters:

  • Sampling Rate: 250 MHz (4 ns per sample)

    • Matches chip duration for proper sampling
    • Nyquist requirement for phase detection
    • Samples per pulse: 250 MHz × 2.1 μs = 525 samples

  • Noise Figure: 10 dB (good performance)

  • RF Gain: 20 dB (LNA amplification)

  • Baseband Gain: 30 dB (total: 50 dB)

  • Load Resistor: 1000 Ω (high impedance)

  • Antenna: Single channel at origin

High Sampling Rate:

PMCW requires much higher sampling than FMCW because:

  • Must capture fast phase transitions (4 ns chips)
  • FMCW samples beat frequency (~MHz)
  • PMCW samples RF directly (~250 MHz minimum)
In [ ]:
# Configure PMCW radar receiver
rx = Receiver(
    fs=250e6,            # Sampling rate: 250 MHz (4 ns per sample, matches chip rate)
    noise_figure=10,     # Noise figure: 10 dB
    rf_gain=20,          # RF gain: 20 dB
    baseband_gain=30,    # Baseband gain: 30 dB (total: 50 dB)
    load_resistor=1000,  # Load resistance: 1000 Ω
    channels=[dict(location=(0, 0, 0))],  # Single RX at origin
)

Combine transmitter and receiver to form the complete PMCW MIMO radar.

Target Configuration¶

Define three targets with high velocities to demonstrate PMCW's large velocity range capability.

Target Parameters¶

High-Velocity Scenario:

These targets have velocities that would exceed FMCW Doppler limits but are easily handled by PMCW:

Target 1 (Very High Closing Speed):

  • Location: (20, 0, 0) m → 20m range
  • Velocity: (-200, 0, 0) m/s → 200 m/s approaching (720 km/h!)
  • RCS: 10 dBsm → Moderate reflector
  • Challenge: Extreme Doppler shift, beyond typical FMCW capability

Target 2 (Stationary, Large):

  • Location: (70, 0, 0) m → 70m range
  • Velocity: (0, 0, 0) m/s → Stationary
  • RCS: 35 dBsm → Very large target (truck, building)
  • Reference: Zero Doppler for calibration

Target 3 (High Receding Speed):

  • Location: (33, 10, 0) m → ~34m range
  • Velocity: (+100, 0, 0) m/s → 100 m/s receding (360 km/h)
  • RCS: 20 dBsm → Large vehicle
  • Note: Positive Doppler (opposite sign)

PMCW Advantage:

Maximum unambiguous velocity for this PMCW radar:

$$v_{max} = \frac{c}{2f_c T_{chip}} = \frac{3 \times 10^8}{2 \times 24.125 \times 10^9 \times 4 \times 10^{-9}} \approx 1550 \text{ m/s}$$

All three targets are well within this range. Compare to typical FMCW: ~30-100 m/s.

# Configure Target 1: Very high closing speed (beyond FMCW capability)

    rcs=10,                 # Radar cross section: 10 dBsm
    phase=0,                # Initial phase: 0 degrees
)

# Configure Target 2: Stationary, large RCS (reference)
target_2 = dict(
    location=(70, 0, 0),    # Position: 70m range
    speed=(0, 0, 0),        # Velocity: 0 m/s (stationary)
    rcs=35,                 # Radar cross section: 35 dBsm (very large)
    phase=0,                # Initial phase: 0 degrees
)

# Configure Target 3: High receding speed
target_3 = dict(
    location=(33, 10, 0),   # Position: ~34m range, 10m Y-offset
    speed=(100, 0, 0),      # Velocity: +100 m/s (360 km/h receding)
    rcs=20,                 # Radar cross section: 20 dBsm
    phase=0,                # Initial phase: 0 degrees
)

# Combine targets for simulation
targets = [target_1, target_2, target_3]

Simulate Baseband Signals¶

Generate PMCW baseband I/Q signals with phase modulation from both MIMO channels.

Simulation Process¶

The simulator computes:

  1. Phase-Modulated Transmission: Each TX applies its phase code
  2. Simultaneous TX: Both channels transmit at same time
  3. Target Returns: Reflections from three targets
  4. Superposition: RX receives sum of both TX signals
  5. Sampling: 250 MHz captures phase transitions

Output Data Structure:

  • Dimensions: [TX channels, pulses, samples]
    • TX Channels: 2 (separate before combining)
    • Pulses: 256
    • Samples: ~525 per pulse (250 MHz × 2.1 μs)

Separate Channel Storage:

RadarSimPy initially stores TX channel contributions separately for analysis, but in reality they transmit simultaneously and must be combined at the receiver.

In [ ]:
# Import radar simulator
from radarsimpy.simulator import sim_radar

# Simulate PMCW radar with 2-channel MIMO and three high-velocity targets
data = sim_radar(radar, targets)

# Extract timestamp and baseband signals
timestamp = data["timestamp"]                       # Time axis [2, 256, 525]
data_matrix = data["baseband"] + data["noise"]     # Complex I/Q + noise [2, 256, 525]

Combine Simultaneous TX Channels¶

Sum baseband contributions from both TX channels to simulate realistic reception.

Realistic MIMO Operation:

In actual hardware:

  • TX1 and TX2 transmit simultaneously at same frequency
  • RX receives superposition of both signals
  • Phase codes overlap in time and frequency
  • Matched filtering separates the contributions

Data Structure:

  • Before combining: [2 TX channels, 256 pulses, 525 samples]
  • After combining: [256 pulses, 525 samples]

The combined baseband contains both codes mixed together, requiring correlation processing to separate them.

In [ ]:
# Combine baseband from both TX channels (simultaneous transmission)
# TX1 and TX2 signals are received together at RX
baseband = data_matrix[0, :, :] + data_matrix[1, :, :]  # [256 pulses, 525 samples]

Radar Signal Processing¶

Apply matched filtering to separate MIMO channels and extract range information.

Matched Filtering (Code Correlation)¶

Range Compression via Correlation:

For PMCW, range is extracted by correlating the received signal with each transmitted code:

$$R[n] = \sum_{k=0}^{N-1} s[k] \cdot c^*[k-n]$$

Where:

  • $s[k]$ = Received baseband (contains both TX1 and TX2)
  • $c[k]$ = Transmitted code (code1 or code2)
  • $n$ = Delay index (range bin)
  • $N$ = Code length (255 chips)

MIMO Channel Separation:

Due to orthogonal codes:

  • Correlate with code1 → Extract TX1 contribution (channel 1)
  • Correlate with code2 → Extract TX2 contribution (channel 2)
  • Low cross-correlation → Minimal interference between channels

Processing Steps:

  1. For each pulse (1-256)
  2. For each range bin (1-255)
  3. Correlate received signal with code
  4. Store result in range profile

This creates a 3D matrix: [channels, pulses, range bins]

Demodulate Channel 1¶

Correlate with code1 to extract TX channel 1 contribution.

In [ ]:
# Initialize range profile storage
# Dimensions: [2 MIMO channels, 256 pulses, 255 range bins]
range_profile = np.zeros(
    (
        radar.array_prop["size"],  # 2 TX channels (MIMO)
        radar.radar_prop["transmitter"].waveform_prop["pulses"],  # 256 pulses
        255,  # 255 range bins (one per chip offset)
    ),
    dtype=complex,  # Complex I/Q data
)

### Matched Filtering for Channel 1 (TX1 with code1) ###

# Loop over all pulses
for pulse_idx in range(0, radar.radar_prop["transmitter"].waveform_prop["pulses"]):
    # Loop over all range bins (delay offsets)
    for bin_idx in range(0, 255):
        # Correlate received signal with code1
        # Extract 255 samples starting at bin_idx
        # Multiply element-wise with code1 and sum (correlation)
        range_profile[0, pulse_idx, bin_idx] = np.sum(
            code1 * baseband[pulse_idx, bin_idx : (bin_idx + 255)]
        )

Demodulate Channel 2¶

Correlate with code2 to extract TX channel 2 contribution.

In [ ]:
### Matched Filtering for Channel 2 (TX2 with code2) ###

# Loop over all pulses
for pulse_idx in range(0, radar.radar_prop["transmitter"].waveform_prop["pulses"]):
    # Loop over all range bins (delay offsets)
    for bin_idx in range(0, 255):
        # Correlate received signal with code2
        # Orthogonal code extracts TX2 contribution
        range_profile[1, pulse_idx, bin_idx] = np.sum(
            code2 * baseband[pulse_idx, bin_idx : (bin_idx + 255)]
        )

Doppler Processing¶

Apply FFT across pulses to extract velocity information for each range bin.

Velocity Extraction:

After matched filtering provides range profiles, Doppler FFT extracts velocity:

$$S[m, n] = \sum_{p=0}^{P-1} R[p, n] \cdot w[p] \cdot e^{-j2\pi mp/P}$$

Where:

  • $p$ = Pulse index (0-255)
  • $n$ = Range bin
  • $w[p]$ = Window function (Chebyshev, 50 dB sidelobes)
  • $m$ = Doppler bin → Velocity

Processing Steps:

  1. Apply Chebyshev window across pulses (sidelobe suppression)
  2. FFT along pulse dimension for each range bin
  3. FFT shift for centered Doppler axis
  4. Result: 3D matrix [channels, Doppler bins, range bins]

Maximum Unambiguous Velocity:

For PMCW with pulse repetition:

$$v_{max} = \frac{c}{2f_c \cdot PRP}$$

Where PRP is the time between consecutive pulses.

In [ ]:
# Import signal processing module
from scipy import signal

# Create Chebyshev window for Doppler FFT (50 dB sidelobe suppression)
doppler_window = signal.windows.chebwin(
    radar.radar_prop["transmitter"].waveform_prop["pulses"], at=50
)

# Initialize range-Doppler map storage
# Dimensions: [2 MIMO channels, 256 Doppler bins, 255 range bins]
range_doppler = np.zeros(np.shape(range_profile), dtype=complex)

# Perform Doppler FFT for each channel and range bin
for ii in range(0, radar.array_prop["size"]):  # Loop over MIMO channels (2)
    for jj in range(0, 255):  # Loop over range bins (255)
        # Apply window, FFT, and shift for each range bin
        range_doppler[ii, :, jj] = np.fft.fftshift(
            np.fft.fft(
                range_profile[ii, :, jj] * doppler_window,  # Window across pulses
                n=radar.radar_prop["transmitter"].waveform_prop["pulses"],  # 256-point FFT
            )
        )

# Calculate maximum unambiguous velocity
# v_max = c / (2 * f_c * PRP)
unambiguous_speed = (
    3e8  # Speed of light
    / radar.radar_prop["transmitter"].waveform_prop["prp"]  # Pulse repetition period
    / 24.125e9  # Carrier frequency
    / 2  # Two-way Doppler
)

  • Y-axis: Velocity (m/s) → Radial velocity (negative = approaching, positive = receding)

Summary¶

In this notebook, you learned how to implement and analyze PMCW radar using RadarSimPy:

Key Takeaways¶

1. PMCW Radar Principles

  • Understood phase modulation vs. frequency modulation
  • Learned BPSK coding (0° and 180° phases)
  • Recognized constant carrier frequency operation
  • Appreciated code-based range measurement

2. PMCW Advantages Over FMCW

  • Large velocity range: ~1550 m/s vs. 30-100 m/s
  • Interference mitigation: Orthogonal codes reduce mutual interference
  • MIMO compatibility: Code separation enables spatial multiplexing
  • Flexible waveform: Adaptive code selection

3. Phase Code Sequences

  • Defined 255-chip binary codes (4 ns per chip)
  • Created orthogonal codes for MIMO (code1, code2)
  • Converted binary ±1 to phase 0°/180°
  • Total code duration: 1.02 μs

4. MIMO Configuration

  • Set up 2 TX channels with orthogonal codes
  • Positioned antennas for virtual array (1m spacing)
  • Configured simultaneous transmission
  • Single RX receives superposition

5. High-Speed Sampling

  • Used 250 MHz sampling (4 ns per sample)
  • Matched chip duration for proper capture
  • Much higher than FMCW requirements
  • Captures fast phase transitions

6. High-Velocity Targets

  • Modeled extreme velocities: ±200 m/s, ±100 m/s
  • Demonstrated beyond-FMCW capability
  • All targets well within PMCW range
  • Clean detection without ambiguity

7. Matched Filtering

  • Performed code correlation for range compression
  • Separated MIMO channels via orthogonal codes
  • Created range profiles for each channel
  • Processing gain from code length (255)

8. Doppler Processing

  • Applied FFT across pulses for velocity
  • Windowing for sidelobe suppression
  • Generated range-Doppler maps
  • Resolved high-velocity targets clearly
